le%3D%22display%3A%20block%3B%20margin-left%3A%20auto%3B%20margin-right%3A%20auto%3B%22%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%0A%0A%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3E%3Cspan%20class%3D%22HwtZe%22%20lang%3D%22en%22%3E%3Cspan%20class%3D%22jCAhz%20ChMk0b%22%3E%3Cspan%20class%3D%22ryNqvb%22%3E%22Numbers%20%26amp%3B%20Oddities%22%0Aa.k.a.%20the%20%22Spooks%20Newsletter%22%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%0A%0A%3Cp%20style%3D%22text-align%3A%20justify%3B%22%3E%3Cspan%20class%3D%22HwtZe%22%20lang%3D%22en%22%3E%3Cspan%20class%3D%22jCAhz%20ChMk0b%22%3E%3Cspan%20class%3D%22ryNqvb%22%3E%22Numbers%20%26amp%3B%20Oddities%22%0Aa.k.a.%20the%20%22Spooks%20Newsletter%22%20is%20a%20newsletter%20for%20the%20members%20of%0Athe%20Utility%20DXers%20Forum%20(UDXF)%2C%20the%20Spooks%20mailing%20list%2C%20HF%0AUnderground%20and%20everyone%20else%20who%20is%20interested%20in%20Numbers%0AStations.%20%22Numbers%20%26amp%3B%20Oddities%22%20covers%20the%20fascinating%20world%20of%0ANumbers%20Stations%20and%20other%20odd%20radio%20signals%20on%0Ashortwave.%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%0A%0A%3Cp%3E%3Cbr%3E%0A%20%3Cstrong%3EIntroduction%3Cbr%3E%0A%3C%2Fstrong%3E%20(%3Cspan%20class%3D%22HwtZe%22%20lang%3D%22en%22%3E%3Cspan%20class%3D%22jCAhz%20ChMk0b%22%3E%3Cspan%20class%3D%22ryNqvb%22%3EThis%20introduction%20is%0Aadapted%20from%20Numbers%20%26amp%3B%20Oddities.)%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%0A%0A%3Cp%20style%3D%22text-align%3A%20justify%3B%22%3E%3Cbr%3E%0A%20My%20first%20encounter%20with%20a%20numbers%20station%20was%20in%20the%20early%201980's.%0AI%20found%20it%20intriguing%20and%20I%20started%20to%20look%20for%20more%20stations.%20I%0Afound%20a%20lot%20of%20them%20and%20I%20still%20follow%20these%20stations.%20Although%0Amany%20stations%20have%20disappeared%20when%20the%20Soviet%20Union%20fell%20apart%2C%0Athere%20are%20still%20stations%20active.%20Note%20that%20not%20all%20numbers%20stations%0Aare%20intelligence%20stations.%3C%2Fp%3E%0A%0A%3Cp%20style%3D%22text-align%3A%20justify%3B%22%3EA%20number%20of%20them%20are%20military%0Astations%20or%20diplomatic%20services.%20We%20founded%20the%20Worldwide%20Utility%0ANews%20Club%20in%20January%201995%20and%20I%20was%20asked%20to%20write%20the%20column%20about%0Adigital%20modes%20but%20I%20would%20rather%20write%20something%20about%20numbers%0Astations%2C%20so%20I%20decided%20to%20do%20both.%20I%20wrote%20my%20first%20%22Numbers%20%26amp%3B%0AOddities%22%20column%20in%20January%201995.%20It%20was%20published%20in%20the%20WUN%0Anewsletter%20in%20February%201995.%20Back%20then%20the%20Spooks%20mailing%20list%20was%0Aone%20of%20the%20sources%20for%20people%20who%20were%20interested%20in%20these%0Astations.%20The%20list%20owner%20and%20I%20thought%20that%20it%20would%20be%20a%20good%20idea%0Ato%20include%20logs%20and%20info%20from%20the%20Spooks%20list%20in%20N%26amp%3BO.%20From%20that%0Aday%20on%20N%26amp%3BO%20appeared%20not%20only%20in%20the%20WUN%20Newsletter%20but%20also%20as%0Aa%20separate%20newsletter%20for%20WUN%20and%20Spooks%20members.%3Cbr%3E%0A%20Lack%20of%20interest%2Finput%20was%20the%20reason%20why%20N%26amp%3BO%20stopped%20as%20a%0Acolumn%20and%20numbers%20stations%20news%20was%20included%20in%20my%20Utility%0ARound-up%20column.%20But%20after%20a%20couple%20of%20months%20N%26amp%3BO%20was%0Areintroduced%20as%20a%20separate%20column.%20The%20N%26amp%3BO%20website%20was%0Aoriginally%20setup%20as%20a%20service%20to%20the%20members%20of%20WUN%20and%20Spooks.%20A%0Aplace%20where%20they%20could%20find%20all%20the%20newsletters%20and%20some%20additional%0Ainformation.%20Later%20on%20I%20have%20also%20included%20a%20logs%20database%2C%0Arecordings%2C%20links%20and%20other%20relevant%20information.%3C%2Fp%3E%0A%0A%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3EWhat%20is%20a%20numbers%20station%3F%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%0A%0A%3Cp%20style%3D%22text-align%3A%20justify%3B%22%3E%3Cbr%3E%0A%20Numbers%20stations%20are%20radio%20stations%20that%20are%20mainly%20active%20on%0Ashortwave.%20Mysterious%20stations%20believed%20to%20be%20owned%20by%20governments%2C%0Athe%20military%20and%2For%20intelligence%20agencies.%20They%20broadcast%20coded%0Amessages%20to%20agents%20or%20military%20personnel%20in%20the%20field%20or%20to%0Aembassies%20or%20wherever%20they%20are.%20Some%20have%20fixed%20schedules%3B%20others%0Aare%20transmitting%20their%20messages%20on%20an%20irregular%20basis.%20The%20messages%0Aconsist%20of%20letter%20groups%20or%20figure%20groups.%20Very%20often%20in%20groups%20of%0A5%20characters%20but%204%20and%203%20groups%20are%20also%20quite%20common.%20Chinese%0Astations%2C%20for%20example%2C%20are%20often%20using%204%20character%20groups.%20The%0Afirst%20reports%20of%20coded%20messages%20date%20back%20to%20World%20War%20I%20when%20the%0Amilitary%20transmitted%20coded%20messages%20via%20HF.%20Most%20of%20the%20involved%0Acountries%20had%20interception%20capabilities%20but%20the%20British%20organized%0Aas%20one%20of%20the%20first%20countries%20an%20intercept%20service.%20The%20intercept%0Astations%20were%20known%20as%20the%20%22Y%22%20stations.%20The%20coded%20messages%20were%0Afurther%20analysed%20by%20the%20crypt-analysts%20of%20Admiralty%20Room%2040.%20In%20the%0Aearly%20days%20not%20all%20messages%20were%20sent%20as%20number%20or%20letter%20groups%0Abut%20also%20as%20text%20phrases%20like%20%22the%20milk%20is%20boiling%20over%22.%0AInteresting%20are%20also%20the%20Indian%20code%20talkers%20who%20sent%20coded%0Amessages%20in%20their%20native%20languages.%20In%20both%20World%20Wars%20%22code%0Atalkers%22%20served%20in%20the%20American%20forces.%20The%20name%20%22code%20talkers%22%20is%0Aespecially%20associated%20with%20the%20Navajo%20speakers%20who%20served%20during%0AWorld%20War%20II%20in%20the%20Pacific%20theatre.%20The%20first%20code%20talkers%2C%0Ahowever%2C%20were%20a%20group%20of%20Choctaw%20Indians%20from%20Oklahoma%20serving%20in%0Athe%20U.S.%20Army%20during%20World%20War%20I.%20These%20Indians%20are%20referred%20to%20as%0AChoctaw%20Code%20Talkers.%20Both%20the%20Choctaw%20Code%20Talkers%20and%20the%20Navajo%0ACode%20Talkers%20used%20Native%20American%20languages%20as%20military%20codes%20that%0Acould%20not%20be%20undeciphered.%20The%20codes%20used%20by%20the%20modern%20numbers%0Astations%20are%20believed%20to%20be%20so%20called%20one-time%20pads.%20A%20one%20time%20pad%0Ais%20the%20only%20currently%20known%20secure%20encryption%20system%2C%20if%20used%0Acorrectly.%20The%20system%20was%20created%20by%20Gilbert%20Vernam%20in%201917.%20The%0Atechnique%20itself%20seems%20to%20be%20much%20older.%20Steven%20M.%20Bellovin%2C%20a%0Aprofessor%20of%20computer%20science%20at%20the%20Columbia%20University%20School%20of%0AEngineering%20found%20a%20code%20book%20from%201882%20that%20describes%20a%20similar%0Atechnique.%20Especially%20during%20the%20Cold%20War%20you%20could%20hear%20a%20host%20of%0Astations%20from%20many%20different%20countries%20like%20the%20U.S.S.R.%2C%20Bulgaria%2C%0ACzecho-Slovakia%2C%20Poland%2C%20Algeria%2C%20Egypt%2C%20U.K.%2C%20U.S.A.%2C%20East%20and%0AWest%20Germany%2C%20Hungary%2C%20France%2C%20Cuba%2C%20Yugoslavia%2C%20North%20and%20South%0AKorea%2C%20Taiwan%2C%20China%2C%20Rumania%2C%20and%20Israel.%20Languages%20used%20were%0ARussian%2C%20English%2C%20German%2C%20French%2C%20Spanish%2C%20various%20other%20Slavic%0Alanguages%2C%20Korean%2C%20Chinese%20and%20even%20Tadjik%20and%20Farsi.%3C%2Fp%3E%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%0A%20%20%20%20%3C%2Farticle%3E%0A%20%20%3C%2Fmain%3E%0A%0A%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%3C%2Fdiv%3E%20%0A%20%20%20%20%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%3Cdiv%20class%3D%22push%22%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%0A%0A%20%20%20%20%3C%2Fdiv%3E%0A%20%20%20%20%0A%20%20%20%20%3Cfooter%20class%3D%22footer%22%3E%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%3Cdiv%20class%3D%22container%22%3E%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%3Cdiv%20class%3D%22row%20text-center%20vertical-align-sm%22%3E%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%3Cdiv%20class%3D%22col-md-1%22%3E%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%3Cp%3E%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%22lice